 To find the height, $h,$ of a pile of three pipes, we first notice that the distance between the centers of adjacent pipes in the same column is equal to the sum of their radii, which is $20$ (since each pipe has a radius of $10$). Let's consider the middle pipe of the three. It sits on two pipes, and its distance from each of those pipes is $10$ (the radius). Thus, the distance from the center of the middle pipe to the center of one of the two pipes that support it is also $10$. This distance is the height of the right triangle formed by the centers of the two supporting pipes and the middle pipe.
Unfortunately, this height is greater than the radius of a pipe (10) and thus inaccessible to the piece of Cartesian graph paper in which these problems are solved.  Consequently, we move on to coordinate geometry, but only for the moment.
Let the center of the rightmost support pipe be located at $(0,0),$ the center of the leftmost support pipe be located at $(d,0),$ and the center of the middle pipe be located at $(x,y).$
Since the centers of the three pipes are at the vertices of an isosceles right triangle, $x$ is half the height of the supporting triangle, and $y$ is the length of the fifth side, one of the legs of the right triangle.

[asy]
unitsize(1inch);
draw((0,0)--dir(0)--dir(45));
draw((rectOn(0,0,10,10)).top--(rectOn(0,0,10,10)).right);
draw((rectOn(0,0,10,10)).top--(rectOn(0,0,10,10)).low);
draw((rectOn(0,0,10,10)).right--(rectOn(0,0,10,10)).low);
draw((rectOn(0,0,10,10)).top--(rectOn(0,0,10,10)).right);
draw((rectOn(0,0,10,10)).top--(rectOn(0,0,10,10)).low);
draw(rightanglemark((0,0),(0,10),(10,0), 10));
[/asy]

In the $xy-$plane, the five circles have centers of $(0,0),$ $(d,0),$ $(x,y),$ $(-d,0),$ and $(-x,y).$ The equations of their boundaries are
\begin{align*}
&x^2+y^2=100,\\
&(x-d)^2+y^2=100,\\
&(x-d)^2+(y-y)^2=100,\\
&( x+d)^2+y^2=100,\\
&( x+d)^2+(y+y)^2=100.
\end{align*}The second and fifth equations are identical, and substitute the value $d=20-h/2$ from the distance between the centers of the OPPOSITE supporting pipes. This gives \begin{align*}(20-h)^2+3y^2 &= 400,\\ 100+100y^2 &=400,\\y^2 &=\frac43,\\ \sqrt{\frac 43}&=\sqrt{a/b},\\a &= 4,\\b &= 3.\end{align*}Thus $ab=\boxed{12}.$

Note that the equations should be
\begin{align*}
&(x-d)/2 = 10,\\
&x^2 + y^2 = 100,\\
&(x+20-h)^2 + y^2 = 100,\\
&(x+20-h)^2 + y^2 = 100,\\
&x^2 + y^2 = 100,\\
&(x+10) d/2 = 10,
\end{align*}and we get $h = 2x.$

